# Obsidian Notes Protocol

The folder `docs/` is an Obsidian Vault. When the user says any of the following, follow this protocol exactly. Do not invent alternative structures.

**Triggers for "organize this session into obsidian" (run the full workflow below):**
- Chinese: **"归档"**, "归一下", "整理到 obsidian", "更新 obsidian"
- English: **"obs"**, "obs it", "update obsidian", "write a journal entry"

**Triggers for "scan code and extract logic":**
- "扫一下 `<file>`", "extract logic from `<file>`", "拆 `<file>` 的逻辑到 Logic"

**Triggers for "generate today's daily plan" (morning report from the inbox):**
- English: **"morning"**, **"plan"**, **"report"**, "plan today"
- Chinese: **"晨报"**, "今日计划", "安排今天"

Note: do NOT interpret the word **"log"** (English) as a trigger — it's a first-class feature name in this app (Log Salad / Log Pizza / Log Gym) and means something entirely different. Only the shortcuts listed above count.

Trigger word disambiguation: `plan` and `report` are generic English words. Only treat them as triggers when they stand alone or with `today`/`for today`/`me`. A sentence like "let me plan the next feature" is NOT a trigger; "plan" / "plan today" / "morning plan please" IS.

## Folder map

```
docs/
├── _Index.md              # MOC — do not overwrite, only add links if structure changes
├── Logic/                 # one note per product-logic rule (the core of the vault)
├── Decisions/             # ADRs — one note per hard call
├── Journal/               # one note per Cursor session, named YYYY-MM-DD-<slug>.md
├── Daily/                 # daily plans (operational, not conceptual) — YYYY-MM-DD.md
├── Templates/             # Logic.md, Decision.md, Journal.md, Daily.md — copy these, never edit
├── note for myself.md     # the raw inbox — user appends freeform thoughts here
└── Peako_*.md             # legacy long-form docs; link but don't fragment
                           # co-owned: cursor edits rarely, claude-design edits Peako_Design_Brief.md
```

## Writing rules

### 1. Every Logic note MUST use `Templates/Logic.md` frontmatter fields
Required frontmatter: `type: logic`, `status`, `tags`, `last_reviewed`, `related`.
Body sections, in this order: **Why → Trigger → Rule → Outputs & side effects → Edge cases → Depends on / Affects → Open questions → Code / UI anchors → Changelog**.

- *Why* is 1–3 sentences tied to user value, not engineering.
- *Rule* MUST be unambiguous — prefer `IF / AND / THEN / ELSE` blocks or a truth table. No prose-only rules.
- *Code anchors* use `src/FileName.jsx` L<start>–L<end>.

### 2. Every Decision note MUST use `Templates/Decision.md`
Use ADR format. Decisions never get deleted; when superseded, mark `status: superseded` and link to the new one.

### 3. Journal entry at end of each session
Filename: `docs/Journal/YYYY-MM-DD-<kebab-slug>.md`. Use `Templates/Journal.md`. Slug describes the session focus, e.g. `2026-04-22-extract-core-logic.md`.

The journal MUST:
- Link every Logic / Decision note touched in that session via `[[…]]`.
- Put unresolved items in *Open threads* as `- [ ] …` so they show up in `_Index.md`'s task query.

### 4. Cross-linking is mandatory
- A new Logic note linked from `Peako_App_Structure.md` or `Peako_Design_Brief.md` → add a one-line mention with `[[Logic/Your-Note]]` where relevant. This keeps the graph connected; without it nothing shows up in Graph view.
- Use Obsidian wikilinks `[[Logic/Streak-Preservation]]`, not relative markdown paths.

### 5. Tags convention
- `#logic` on every Logic note, plus a feature tag like `#feature/feed`, `#feature/challenge`, `#feature/log`, `#feature/progress`.
- `#decision` on every Decision note.
- `#journal` on every Journal note.
- Avoid free-form tags — pick from existing ones unless the user explicitly adds a new category.

### 6. Never touch
- `docs/_Index.md` — only add links when a whole new folder/category appears. Dataview queries update automatically.
- `docs/Templates/*` — templates are read-only references; copy them, don't edit in place.
- Legacy `docs/Peako_*.md` — preserve as-is; new info goes into `Logic/` / `Decisions/` and links back.

## Co-authoring with the design AI

A second AI (Claude, in a separate design tool at a different workstation) also writes to this vault via git pull/push. Coexistence rules:

- **Append, never rewrite.** When updating a Logic or Decision note, only modify sections you authored in this session. Do not reorganize, reformat, or collapse prior entries regardless of author.
- **Author marker in frontmatter.** Journal entries use `participants: [me, cursor]` or `participants: [me, claude-design]` depending on who ran the session. Never merge two authors into one Journal file — each session is one file, one author.
- **Changelog lines include author tag.** In Logic-note `## Changelog` sections and Decision-note amendments, prefix your line with `[cursor]` or `[claude-design]`:
  - `- 2026-04-24 [cursor] — locked rule after ADR-009`
  - `- 2026-04-24 [claude-design] — updated Code/UI anchors after screen redesign`
- **ADR numbers are a shared sequence.** Before creating a new ADR, `git pull`, then check the highest existing `ADR-<n>` in `Decisions/` and use `n+1`. If you hit a collision on push, the loser renames to `n+2` and updates inbound wikilinks.
- **Journal filenames must not collide.** Same-day sessions from different authors differentiate via slug, e.g. `2026-04-24-cursor-streak-refactor.md` and `2026-04-24-design-feed-redesign.md`. Never append `-1` / `-2`.
- **Don't touch each other's scope without a handoff.** Cursor owns `src/` logic extraction; the design AI owns `Peako_Design_Brief.md` and screen-level anchors inside Logic notes. If you need to edit the other's territory, leave a `TODO: handoff to <other>` in the relevant section and surface it in the Journal's *Open threads*.
- **Trigger words apply to whoever is in session.** If the user says `归档` / `obs` to the design AI, it runs the workflow there; Cursor picks up the Journal entry on next pull. Don't re-run the archive on pull — it's already been archived.

## The "整理到 obsidian" workflow

When asked to organize a session, run this sequence:

1. **Scan the conversation** for: (a) new/changed product rules, (b) decisions made or opened, (c) code changes touching logic.
2. **For each piece of product logic** touched, either create a new `Logic/<Name>.md` from the template, or update the existing one (bump `last_reviewed`, append a changelog line).
3. **For each hard call** that was made or deferred, create/update `Decisions/ADR-<n>-<slug>.md`.
4. **Write one Journal entry** `Journal/YYYY-MM-DD-<slug>.md` summarizing the session and linking everything touched.
5. **Report back**: tell the user exactly which files were created/modified with a one-line reason each.

## The "extract logic from <file>" workflow

When asked to scan code and extract logic:

1. Read the target file end-to-end.
2. Identify each decision point / branch / magic number / ruleset (e.g. a `switch`, a reward table, a state transition, a time-based rule). Each one becomes one Logic note.
3. Do NOT document pure presentational code (animations, CSS, layout) as Logic. Logic = rules that affect product behavior.
4. For each, fill in *Why* by inferring user-facing impact; if uncertain, write `TODO: confirm with PM` and leave `status: draft`.
5. Cross-link: if two logics share inputs/outputs, add each to the other's `Depends on / Affects`.
6. End with a Journal entry summarizing what was extracted.

## The "daily plan" workflow

When asked for a `morning` / `plan` / `report` / `晨报`:

### 1. Read these inputs, in this order
1. `docs/note for myself.md` — the raw inbox. This is the primary input.
2. The most recent file in `docs/Daily/` (yesterday's plan, if any) — for carryover.
3. The 3 most recent `docs/Journal/*.md` — for recent-session context.
4. `docs/Peako_Open_Decisions.md` — to cross-reference open product calls.
5. `git log --since="2 days ago" --oneline` — to see what changed while the user was away (possibly from the other AI).

### 2. Classify every inbox entry into one bucket
- `decision-needed` — a hard call that deserves an ADR
- `design-task` — visual/interaction work (likely for claude-design to own)
- `code-task` — implementation work (likely for cursor to own)
- `research-question` — needs more info before it's actionable
- `deferred` — entry explicitly says 之后 / later / 放到后面
- `status-update` — just a note about progress, no action needed
- `done` — already accomplished, can be archived

### 3. Prioritize
- **Top 3** = the three items with the highest combination of (urgency × user-value × unblocks-others). Never more than 3. Each must cite its source (which inbox entry, which Journal thread, which open decision).
- **Secondary** = everything else that's actionable today.
- **Open questions → candidate ADRs** = `decision-needed` items. Name the expected ADR number (current max + 1).
- **Stale** = inbox items ≥ 7 days old with no movement. Suggest defer / escalate / close.
- **Carryover** = yesterday's top-3 items not marked done. If they've carried ≥ 3 days, demote to Secondary and flag.

### 4. Cross-link aggressively
- If an inbox item matches an existing `Logic/` or `Decisions/` note, link it rather than duplicating context.
- If it's a candidate ADR, name the slug you'd use.

### 5. Write the file
Path: `docs/Daily/YYYY-MM-DD.md` (or `YYYY-MM-DD-<slot>.md` if the file already exists — e.g. `-afternoon`). Use `Templates/Daily.md`. Set `author:` to `cursor` or `claude-design`.

### 6. Report back in chat
Summarize the **Top 3** (bullets, ≤ 1 line each) and the count of secondary / open-question / stale items. Link the generated file. Do NOT paste the full file into chat — the user reads it in Obsidian.

### 7. Do NOT
- Do NOT modify `docs/note for myself.md`. The user curates that manually.
- Do NOT create Logic/Decision notes as a side effect of the plan. That's the `obs` workflow. The daily plan only *suggests* which entries deserve to become ADRs.
- Do NOT commit/push. The user decides when.

## Examples of well-scoped Logic notes

- ✅ `Logic/Coin-Reward-Rule.md` — "pizza earns 2 coins, others earn 10" (a rule with user impact)
- ✅ `Logic/Streak-Preservation.md` — "what keeps a streak alive" (a product rule)
- ✅ `Logic/Challenge-Sequencing.md` — "can user tap challenge 2 before finishing 1" (an IA rule)
- ❌ `Logic/PostCard-Animation.md` — presentational, belongs in design brief, not Logic
- ❌ `Logic/useState-setup.md` — implementation trivia, not a product rule
